  "content": "# A Resource List for Causality in Statistics and Data Science\n\n## Table of Contents\n- [Editor's Selection](#editors-selection)\n- [Books](#books)\n- [Papers](#papers-general)\n- [Software](#software)\n- [Datasets](#datasets)\n- [MOOCs](#moocs)\n\n## Editor's Selection\nHighly important resources, ordered from beginner to advanced:\n\n* **The Book of Why: The New Science of Cause and Effect (2018)**  \n  Judea Pearl and Mackenzie  \n  An accessible introduction to causal inference for a general audience.\n\n* **The Seven Tools of Causal Inference, with Reflections on Machine Learning**  \n  Judea Pearl  \n  Communications of the ACM, March 2019, Vol. 62 No. 3, Pages 54-60  \n  A concise overview of the key tools in causal inference.\n\n* **Causal Inference in Statistics: A Primer (2016)**  \n  Pearl, Glymour and Jewell  \n  A more technical introduction to causal inference concepts.\n\n* **Nobel Memorial Economics Prize 2021 on causal discovery**  \n  Scientific summary: Answering Causal Questions Using Observational Data  \n  (David Card, Joshua Angrist, and Guido Imbens)\n\n## Books\n\n* **Applied Causal Inference Powered by ML and AI (2024)**  \n  V. Chernozhukov, C. Hansen, N. Kallus, M. Spindler, V. Syrgkanis\n\n* **A First Course in Causal Inference (2023)**  \n  Peng Ding\n\n* **Causal Inference & Discovery in Python (2023)**  \n  From Machine Learning & Pearlian Perspective  \n  Aleksander Molak\n\n* **Causal Inference for The Brave and True (2022)**  \n  Matheus Facure\n\n* **The Effect: An Introduction to Research Design and Causality (2021)**  \n  Nick Huntington-Klein\n\n* **Causal Inference: What If (2020)**  \n  Hernán & Robins\n\n* **Elements of Causal Inference: Foundations and Learning Algorithms (2017)**  \n  Jonas Peters, Dominik Janzing and Bernhard Schoelkopf\n\n## Papers\n\n* **Causal inference for time series (2023)**  \n  Jakob Runge et al.  \n  Nature Reviews Earth & Environment\n\n* **Double Machine Learning and Automated Confounder Selection -- A Cautionary Tale (2023)**  \n  Paul Hünermund et al.\n\n* **The Seven Tools of Causal Inference, with Reflections on Machine Learning (2019)**  \n  Judea Pearl  \n  Communications of the ACM\n\n* **Causal diagrams for empirical research (1995)**  \n  Judea Pearl\n\n* **Statistics and Causal Inference (1986)**  \n  Paul W. Holland  \n  Journal of the American Statistical Association\n\n## Machine Learning\n\n* **Causal Reasoning and Large Language Models: Opening a New Frontier for Causality (2023)**  \n  Emre Kıcıman, Robert Ness, Amit Sharma, Chenhao Tan\n\n* **Causal Reinforcement Learning: A Survey (2023)**  \n  Zhihong Deng, Jing Jiang, Guodong Long, Chengqi Zhang\n\n* **Causal Machine Learning: A Survey and Open Problems (2022)**  \n  Jean Kaddour, Aengus Lynch, Qi Liu, Matt J. Kusner, Ricardo Silva\n\n* **Causality for Machine Learning (2020)**  \n  Bernhard Schölkopf\n\n## Software\n\n### Causal Discovery\n\n* **Causal-learn: Causal Discovery in Python**  \n  Spirtes & CMU & Team\n\n* **Tigramite** – Causal inference and causal discovery for time series datasets\n\n* **The Causal Discovery Toolbox (CDT)**  \n  A package for causal inference in graphs and in the pairwise settings\n\n### Microsoft Research: PyWhy\n\n* **DoWhy** is a Python library for causal inference\n\n* **EconML** is a Python package for estimating heterogeneous treatment effects\n\n* **ShowWhy** - UI on top of DoWhy, EconML\n\n### Causal Impact and Observational\n\n* **DoubleML** in Python/R package\n\n* **CausalML**: A Python Package for Uplift Modeling and Causal Inference with ML\n\n* **CausalImpact**: An R package for causal inference using Bayesian structural time-series models\n\n## Datasets\n\n* **R causaldata**  \n  Nick Huntington-Klein, Malcolm Barrett  \n  Example datasets from some of the Causality textbooks\n\n* **Cause-effect pairs database**  \n  Joris M. Mooij et al. (2016)  \n  Database with cause-effect pairs for benchmarking\n\n## MOOCs\n\n* **Mixtape sessions**  \n  Free Course Material\n\n* **A Crash Course in Causality: Inferring Causal Effects from Observational Data**  \n  Coursera\n\n* **Measuring Causal Effects in the Social Sciences**  \n  Coursera\n\n* **Probabilistic Graphical Models Specialization**  \n  Daphne Koller, Coursera\n\nThis resource list is continuously updated. For more comprehensive information on each resource, please visit the linked websites or search for the titles online.
